1
00:00:02,190 --> 00:00:09,580
Tonight I want to continue looking at the third section of the Satipatthana Sutta, the contemplation of mind.

2
00:00:11,522 --> 00:00:22,056
Last night we looked at the first three exercises to know when the mind is or is not under the influence of greed, anger and delusion.

3
00:00:23,149 --> 00:00:33,338
The next line of the Sutta reads, One understands contracted mind as contracted mind and distracted mind as distracted mind.

4
00:00:35,561 --> 00:00:45,789
Contracted mind is understood as being under the influence of dullness and lethargy, while distracted mind is what we normally call restlessness.

5
00:00:48,432 --> 00:00:53,156
We can distinguish this exercise from our work with the corresponding hindrances.

6
00:00:54,131 --> 00:00:58,595
When we keep falling asleep we're dealing with the hindrance of dullness and lethargy.

7
00:00:59,837 --> 00:01:04,941
The mind will be contracted but we won't be able to discern this because we're too dozy.

8
00:01:04,962 --> 00:01:14,790
After working mindfully with the hindrance for a period we may find that awareness steadies and we can observe the state quite closely.

9
00:01:16,253 --> 00:01:20,496
We still feel dozy, dull, but we're not asleep.

10
00:01:21,397 --> 00:01:23,058
We're aware of dullness.

11
00:01:25,435 --> 00:01:27,938
We might also be aware of the underlying feelings.

12
00:01:29,138 --> 00:01:30,721
They're usually pleasant feelings.

13
00:01:32,403 --> 00:01:39,311
To rest attention in the third satipatthana, we focus on the mind that knows these pleasant feelings.

14
00:01:41,653 --> 00:01:44,096
Contracted mind describes this very well.

15
00:01:45,156 --> 00:01:47,118
It only knows those pleasant feelings.

16
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:49,501
It doesn't know anything else.

17
00:01:50,257 --> 00:01:55,528
It's as if we've retreated from the world, locked ourselves into a comforting stupor.

18
00:01:58,233 --> 00:02:01,299
In contrast to this, we have distracted mind.

19
00:02:02,501 --> 00:02:10,056
When we're fidgeting or can't keep track of the multitude of thoughts that keep cropping up, then we're dealing with the hindrance of restlessness.

20
00:02:11,116 --> 00:02:23,912
Again, after working with this mindfully, awareness may come to rest in the third satipatthana, and we can then experience the mind that's continually moving, searching for something.

21
00:02:25,734 --> 00:02:34,746
It's the same mind state in both cases, but because awareness is now focused on the mind state, those distractions can't get very far.

22
00:02:35,986 --> 00:02:40,633
They only disturb us to the extent necessary to register in awareness.

23
00:02:43,836 --> 00:02:53,209
In contrast to the pleasant feelings associated with the contracted mind the feelings associated with the distracted mind are usually unpleasant.

24
00:02:54,790 --> 00:03:02,340
The habit is to resist unpleasant feelings and so the mind moves around trying to get away from the disturbance.

25
00:03:03,542 --> 00:03:10,670
Whereas in the case of dullness and lethargy the mind contracts around the underlying pleasant feelings.

26
00:03:14,735 --> 00:03:20,164
The two states can also be contrasted in terms of subjectivity and objectivity.

27
00:03:22,688 --> 00:03:27,157
In the contracted mind, the mind is subjectively orientated.

28
00:03:28,419 --> 00:03:29,501
It's all me.

29
00:03:31,564 --> 00:03:34,971
There's no room for anything else, anything objective.

30
00:03:36,367 --> 00:03:49,855
If it could summon the energy to describe experience, it might say this, because we use the word this to describe what's immediate, present, within my grasp, mine.

31
00:03:49,895 --> 00:03:55,187
This chair I'm sitting on, this idea I'm considering.

32
00:03:57,461 --> 00:04:07,655
We use the word that to describe something that's external, not part of me, that chair you're sitting on, that idea you're putting forward.

33
00:04:09,497 --> 00:04:11,680
The distracted mind is looking outwards.

34
00:04:12,520 --> 00:04:14,503
Its orientation is objective.

35
00:04:15,906 --> 00:04:19,389
It's searching the external world to escape its own displeasure.

36
00:04:20,911 --> 00:04:24,617
Each moment it lands on something new to call that.

37
00:04:27,567 --> 00:04:32,351
At times we might see the mind transiting between the two states.

38
00:04:34,295 --> 00:04:41,603
One moment it contracts around a pleasant feeling, perceives it as subjective, as this and mine.

39
00:04:43,665 --> 00:04:49,591
Next moment it detects an unpleasant feeling and bounces away, calling it that.

40
00:04:51,478 --> 00:05:03,153
When awareness is steady enough to see these transitions, we get a chance to see how the mind constructs such radically different versions of reality based on feelings.

41
00:05:05,615 --> 00:05:11,843
Pleasant feelings are perceived as here, within our grasp, internal, mine.

42
00:05:13,305 --> 00:05:15,326
They are readily labelled as this.

43
00:05:17,500 --> 00:05:28,074
These unpleasant feelings are perceived as external, objective, something that can be pushed away, not mine, labelled as that.

44
00:05:29,836 --> 00:05:37,786
This and that, subjectivity and objectivity, mine and not mine, they feed off one another.

45
00:05:40,247 --> 00:05:52,262
As the Buddha says in the discourse on the destruction of craving when this exists, that comes to be with the arising of this, that arises.

46
00:05:56,468 --> 00:06:09,343
The better we can steady awareness around contracted and distracted states of mind the better we can see how craving causes us to construct two separate worlds

47
00:06:11,365 --> 00:06:14,670
One is internal, contracted around pleasant feeling.

48
00:06:15,831 --> 00:06:21,918
The other is external, extensive, allowing the mind bounce from one object to another.

49
00:06:27,346 --> 00:06:34,757
When we fully understand these minute movements of mind, we'll see through the delusion caused by craving.

50
00:06:37,807 --> 00:06:59,533
When consciousness stops even for a moment, clinging to the idea of this self as the ultimate reference points for the world, then the multitude of that's, that person, that challenge, that obligation also disappear and we're liberated from the stress of false view.

51
00:07:01,615 --> 00:07:07,021
It might only be momentary, but it punches a little hole in delusions.

52
00:07:10,629 --> 00:07:17,079
Thus we should welcome lethargy, dullness and restlessness whenever they come our way.

53
00:07:17,139 --> 00:07:23,627
Work mindfully with them until the mind can rest in the third satipatthana.

54
00:07:24,769 --> 00:07:34,242
Teach us what is meant by contracted and distracted mind and how we create our world out of pleasant and unpleasant feelings.

55
00:07:37,663 --> 00:07:48,735
The next instruction is, one understands exalted mind as exalted mind and unexalted mind as unexalted mind.

56
00:07:52,478 --> 00:08:04,110
An exalted mind, sometimes termed great mind, is based in one of the four Brahma Vihara, the divine abodes, the ways that wisdom manifests in the world.

57
00:08:05,507 --> 00:08:11,112
The divine abodes all have goodwill as their basis, wishing ourselves and others well.

58
00:08:12,814 --> 00:08:23,384
Metta, friendliness, is the form goodwill takes by default, when there is no especially joyful, sad or challenging atmosphere associated with the encounter.

59
00:08:25,607 --> 00:08:30,911
If we meet someone who is going through a hard time, goodwill takes the hue of compassion.

60
00:08:32,013 --> 00:08:34,215
We wish that their troubles might cease.

61
00:08:35,697 --> 00:08:41,849
When there's something to celebrate, goodwill takes on the flavour of modita, appreciative joy.

62
00:08:43,552 --> 00:08:56,878
And when we come across limitations or unskilfulness in ourselves or others, the response is equanimity, a tender understanding and acceptance of worldly imperfection.

63
00:09:01,162 --> 00:09:14,216
On this side of liberation, we'll often miss the mark in relationship, believe we're acting with pure goodwill, but in reality hooked by what's termed the near enemy of the Brahma Vihara.

64
00:09:16,559 --> 00:09:19,523
Friendliness is often mixed in with attachment.

65
00:09:20,965 --> 00:09:28,332
We're anxious to sustain the relationship, needing the other person's company, good humour, esteem, etc.,

66
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:34,125
Often we don't even notice the subtle expectations we have of our friends.

67
00:09:35,946 --> 00:09:42,652
It's only when we feel let down that we realise how many strings we were attaching to our acts of friendship.

68
00:09:46,696 --> 00:09:48,758
Pity can masquerade as compassion.

69
00:09:49,899 --> 00:10:00,008
We overblow the problem, underestimate the person's resources, forgetting that their essence has not been diminished by whatever misfortune has come their way

70
00:10:01,642 --> 00:10:07,770
We think they can't cope without our help, but then get overwhelmed and feel burdened by responsibility.

71
00:10:11,755 --> 00:10:14,801
The near enemy of mudita is excitement.

72
00:10:16,202 --> 00:10:21,250
We build too much out of the occasion, go to excess in our efforts to celebrate.

73
00:10:21,309 --> 00:10:28,240
Finally, we can mistake indifference for equanimity.

74
00:10:29,923 --> 00:10:40,780
When some challenge comes up in our relationship we ignore this or shrug our shoulders rather than feel whatever disappointment, fear or anger may have been evoked.

75
00:10:41,682 --> 00:10:50,115
Work through those feelings to acceptance of the limitations of the relationship.

76
00:10:50,134 --> 00:10:58,327
To get to know the exalted mind we can practice metta but with a degree of curiosity about our experience.

77
00:11:00,855 --> 00:11:04,083
you might experiment with the Buddha's guidance for metta practice.

78
00:11:06,830 --> 00:11:18,256
One dwells suffusing one quarter with a mind filled with loving kindness, then a second, then a third, and a fourth quarter.

79
00:11:18,793 --> 00:11:37,472
Thus one abides, suffusing the whole world, up, down and across, everywhere, all around, with a mind filled with loving-kindness, expanded, immeasurable, free from hatred and ill-will.

80
00:11:40,395 --> 00:11:42,857
This doesn't mention any categories of people.

81
00:11:43,818 --> 00:11:47,923
In fact, it doesn't mention people at all, not even other beings.

82
00:11:48,764 --> 00:11:54,208
It puts aside the usual ideas of self and other that we use in meta-practice.

83
00:11:55,610 --> 00:12:04,198
Instead, we use the concept of space and radiate loving-kindness up, down and across, everywhere, all around.

84
00:12:06,321 --> 00:12:12,486
Whatever this might involve at an ultimate level, we can also see this as an exercise in imagination.

85
00:12:14,089 --> 00:12:18,113
We're training ourselves to imagine a world pervaded with kindness.

86
00:12:19,628 --> 00:12:23,913
If we imagine this often enough, it will become our inner reality.

87
00:12:26,517 --> 00:12:32,904
If and when metta seems stable, we can become curious about the mind that practices metta.

88
00:12:35,607 --> 00:12:39,533
The Buddha describes this as expanded, immeasurable.

89
00:12:42,056 --> 00:12:49,044
Can you sense how imagining space around you requires a mind that itself is spacious?

90
00:12:50,812 --> 00:12:54,259
The mind expands to meet the space it imagines.

91
00:12:57,302 --> 00:12:59,046
But of course there will be challenges.

92
00:13:00,688 --> 00:13:04,936
Our imagination will reach limits where we cannot conceive of kindness.

93
00:13:06,457 --> 00:13:08,981
This shows us the unexalted mind.

94
00:13:11,446 --> 00:13:15,251
At times the unexalted mind involves some form of ill will.

95
00:13:16,480 --> 00:13:20,004
We project demons into the space around us instead of good wishes.

96
00:13:20,043 --> 00:13:25,570
So we get frightened if these demons are angry that they're preventing us practicing Netta.

97
00:13:26,692 --> 00:13:31,356
Or we might just turn away from the difficulty as the mind shrinks into dullness.

98
00:13:34,581 --> 00:13:38,504
At other times, the unexalted mind may involve greed.

99
00:13:40,139 --> 00:13:49,837
We project an exalted, saintly image of ourselves into the space around and then believe ourselves to be this great person with a big open heart.

100
00:13:52,023 --> 00:14:02,383
We might also get excited by all the good deeds we could do and all the people we could benefit, in which case restlessness forms the basis for the unexalted mind.

101
00:14:05,434 --> 00:14:11,408
Alternatively, when our imagination reaches its limit, we start wondering what's going on.

102
00:14:12,530 --> 00:14:14,554
Is there really all this space around me?

103
00:14:15,576 --> 00:14:17,240
Can I really fill it with metta?

104
00:14:19,605 --> 00:14:24,878
In this case, the unexalted mind is based in the hindrance of doubt.

105
00:14:29,717 --> 00:14:38,049
Because the Sutta asks us to get to know both the exalted and unexalted mind, we don't have to think of the latter as a failure.

106
00:14:39,371 --> 00:14:42,496
In fact, the more curious we can get about it, the better.

107
00:14:43,938 --> 00:14:48,065
The positive attitude helps us work through whichever hindrance emerges.

108
00:14:52,270 --> 00:14:56,636
The unexalted mind isn't necessarily based on any of the hindrances.

109
00:14:58,168 --> 00:15:04,316
We can also experience this as quite peaceful, the mind as simply knowing.

110
00:15:06,298 --> 00:15:11,604
There isn't active goodwill being generated, but there's no ill will either.

111
00:15:15,028 --> 00:15:23,518
The Buddha's pairing of exalted and unexalted mind helps us foster a beneficial relationship between these.

112
00:15:25,152 --> 00:15:29,739
At one moment we pervade the space around us with warm good wishes.

113
00:15:32,001 --> 00:15:36,268
The next moment we get curious about the mind that practices metta.

114
00:15:37,990 --> 00:15:42,015
We sense the expanded consciousness, the exalted mind.

115
00:15:44,440 --> 00:15:48,826
Quietly the image of space filled with metta disappears.

116
00:15:51,269 --> 00:15:54,855
For a while there is just the knowing mind

117
00:15:56,505 --> 00:16:01,010
Awareness gradually lands on other aspects of the being who meditates.

118
00:16:02,312 --> 00:16:08,600
Feelings, body, perception, unexalted mind.

119
00:16:12,105 --> 00:16:18,211
The memory of the vast metaphil space fosters acceptance of our conditional nature.

120
00:16:19,453 --> 00:16:25,280
Gratitude for the Dhamma which allows our being learn its true nature.

121
00:16:29,024 --> 00:16:38,375
Metta flows into the being with unexalted mind until it is ready once again to pervade the space around it with goodwill.

122
00:16:40,356 --> 00:16:51,048
Thus unexalted mind can provide a skilful break during metta practice, allowing us to rest and recharge our metta batteries.

123
00:16:57,390 --> 00:17:08,384
The next instruction is to understand unsurpassed mind as unsurpassed mind and surpassed mind as surpassed mind.

124
00:17:12,008 --> 00:17:19,737
This is often taken as referring to jhana practices where the highest jhana represents the unsurpassed mind.

125
00:17:21,926 --> 00:17:41,192
In his book Satipatthana, a practical guide, Anaglio suggests that this can also be used in Vipassana, asking ourselves, has the mind been developed to its maximum capacity for this particular meditation, or can we continue to develop?

126
00:17:45,057 --> 00:17:50,904
The standard Vipassana instructions don't explicitly include developing the mind.

127
00:17:52,218 --> 00:17:55,442
We are simply to register what we experience without judgment.

128
00:17:56,983 --> 00:18:01,368
Within non-judgmental awareness the mind develops of its own accord.

129
00:18:03,270 --> 00:18:10,119
The factors of enlightenment strengthen as the mind moves through hindrances towards greater clarity and ease.

130
00:18:12,883 --> 00:18:17,929
When the factors of enlightenment are strong we have the unsurpassed mind.

131
00:18:19,751 --> 00:18:20,992
There is mindfulness

132
00:18:21,698 --> 00:18:24,221
We can maintain focus in present experience.

133
00:18:25,181 --> 00:18:28,704
We're not repeatedly getting lost in thought or falling asleep.

134
00:18:30,846 --> 00:18:32,008
There is concentration.

135
00:18:33,410 --> 00:18:37,594
We can focus on some aspect of experience and track this.

136
00:18:39,895 --> 00:18:40,997
There is equanimity.

137
00:18:42,239 --> 00:18:50,727
We're able to maintain an objective, balanced stance rather than being sucked in by desires identified by views and thoughts.

138
00:18:52,984 --> 00:18:54,146
There is tranquility.

139
00:18:55,288 --> 00:18:59,653
Preferring calm to excitement, we keep dropping desires and aversions.

140
00:19:01,256 --> 00:19:02,238
There is energy.

141
00:19:03,338 --> 00:19:10,189
We have the will and resources needed to maintain mindfulness, concentration and the other factors of enlightenment.

142
00:19:12,070 --> 00:19:13,472
There is investigation.

143
00:19:14,734 --> 00:19:19,060
The mind is intelligent, curious, discerning.

144
00:19:21,064 --> 00:19:21,944
There is joy.

145
00:19:23,224 --> 00:19:27,269
we are interested in experience, glad to be learning the Dhamma.

146
00:19:31,315 --> 00:19:41,327
This exercise in the Satipatthana Sutta asks us to look back into that well-balanced mind, to recognise it as unsurpassed.

147
00:19:45,073 --> 00:19:52,201
The word unsurpassed might make the exercise seem impossible, as if we should be looking into the mind of a saint,

148
00:19:53,988 --> 00:20:00,194
But we can interpret it to mean that awareness can't detect a flaw that can't be fixed.

149
00:20:02,719 --> 00:20:08,705
If awareness detects grasping, the factors of enlightenment can step up to put this right.

150
00:20:11,169 --> 00:20:18,897
For example, we could shift focus, let attention rest in the breath or other neutral calming sensations.

151
00:20:20,244 --> 00:20:25,971
Energy could be stepped up a gear in order to resist the pull of desire, the push of aversion.

152
00:20:27,733 --> 00:20:37,525
Mindfulness could become more alert to the fading away of experience, moment after moment, which helps us acknowledge the futility of grasping.

153
00:20:39,547 --> 00:20:44,633
Equanimity might draw attention back from detail to see the larger picture.

154
00:20:48,140 --> 00:20:52,727
These adjustments happen naturally, organically, without forcing.

155
00:20:54,269 --> 00:20:58,296
The factors work together as a team to restore their formation.

156
00:21:00,038 --> 00:21:03,523
Panti's wild geese analogy is very useful here.

157
00:21:05,207 --> 00:21:12,679
At times their V-shaped formation gets disturbed, some flying too fast, others going too slow.

158
00:21:13,637 --> 00:21:16,544
But then the instinct for coordination comes to the fore.

159
00:21:17,605 --> 00:21:22,756
Various birds come forward, others fall back, until order is restored.

160
00:21:24,338 --> 00:21:32,355
The flock needs to get to their destination, and each individual is willing to fall into line with that overriding objective.

161
00:21:39,067 --> 00:21:42,794
In the same way, the factors of enlightenment get scattered.

162
00:21:43,474 --> 00:21:51,286
For example, when we get too curious and fall prey to the desire to know and understand experience more clearly.

163
00:21:51,306 --> 00:21:59,618
Unwittingly, we start forcing our agenda, put ourselves under pressure to hurry towards enlightenment.

164
00:22:01,201 --> 00:22:03,304
This is the surpassed mind.

165
00:22:05,191 --> 00:22:17,968
But mindfulness detects the problem and then the adjustments start, changing focus, widening attention, noticing that everything is always slipping away, fading out.

166
00:22:20,480 --> 00:22:36,344
Our overriding objective is to maintain the objective observer stance and so traits like curiosity and tranquility take a back seat as the mind steadies itself to resist the pull of grasping.

167
00:22:39,890 --> 00:22:48,563
If order can be restored, if we again sense awareness brushing against experience rather than digging in, shaping it,

168
00:22:49,656 --> 00:22:55,203
then we can again reflect that the mind at the moment is unsurpassed.

169
00:22:56,807 --> 00:23:00,471
It knows how to maintain its own objectivity.

170
00:23:05,798 --> 00:23:12,086
Anaglio describes the unsurpassed mind as one which can continue to develop.

171
00:23:14,512 --> 00:23:24,201
For example, we can use the unsurpassed mind to develop one of the factors of enlightenment or a virtue like patience.

172
00:23:26,423 --> 00:23:28,205
Often we're developing wisdom.

173
00:23:29,827 --> 00:23:40,538
We're seeing that sensations and feelings, moods and emotions, thoughts and images, all experience arises and passes away.

174
00:23:41,986 --> 00:23:44,849
that any attempt to cling brings dukkha.

175
00:23:47,192 --> 00:23:52,119
In other words, we're learning about the three characteristics of existence.

176
00:23:53,280 --> 00:23:55,724
Anicca, dukkha, anatta.

177
00:23:56,746 --> 00:24:06,419
Transience, unsatisfactoriness and not-self.

178
00:24:06,439 --> 00:24:10,845
But there comes a stage when we can no longer sustain equanimity.

179
00:24:12,192 --> 00:24:18,839
The hindrances are threatening to overpower us, and we sense it best to draw the meditation to a close.

180
00:24:20,281 --> 00:24:28,832
Here we have an example of the surpassed mind, one which, using Anaglio's description, cannot be further developed.

181
00:24:30,053 --> 00:24:36,039
We've run out of meditative steam, need to let daily life recharge our batteries.

182
00:24:41,301 --> 00:24:51,497
What I often do here is to make the determination to wait until there is equanimity in the movement from sitting to standing.

183
00:24:54,221 --> 00:25:05,217
For as long as I feel impatience, the desire to plunge straight into daily life, I keep relaxing, allowing that desire to burn off.

184
00:25:06,444 --> 00:25:18,076
reminding myself that this is the surpassed mind, the mind that has reached its limit of development, a worthy satipatthana for mindfulness.

185
00:25:21,558 --> 00:25:34,832
Aversions and judgments may emerge, but again I note these, reminding myself that this surpassed mind is what I have to work with in daily life, so I might as well make friends with it,

186
00:25:37,900 --> 00:25:45,909
At some stage I notice the mind readying itself to stand and the body starting to sway or the eyes to open.

187
00:25:47,570 --> 00:25:53,097
Until it happens I never know how the body will actually do the business of standing up.

188
00:25:55,359 --> 00:26:04,431
These movements are sensed as an equanimous follow-on to the earlier decision to bring the meditation to a close.

189
00:26:08,393 --> 00:26:22,288
These final minutes of the meditation are an exercise in making peace with limitations, accepting that the mind has done its job and cannot be further developed in this meditation setting.

190
00:26:24,431 --> 00:26:29,156
The transition back into daily life is wiser and more peaceful as a result.

191
00:26:33,541 --> 00:26:36,325
Knowing our limitations is a great asset in life.

192
00:26:37,417 --> 00:26:45,887
knowing when we need to stop pushing ourselves to achieve some goal, when we need to step back, rest, recharge our batteries.

193
00:26:48,391 --> 00:26:56,500
The label surpassed mind can also help us make peace with the mental limitations we detect in daily life.

194
00:26:57,501 --> 00:27:02,126
For example, when we sense the mind as dull or stuck or lazy.

195
00:27:03,759 --> 00:27:08,406
We might not even have enough energy to work out which of the hindrances is overpowering us.

196
00:27:09,848 --> 00:27:12,833
We just know we're not in the most wholesome condition.

197
00:27:15,217 --> 00:27:30,679
The phrase surpassed mind lets us put all such states into a box, helps us see them objectively, draw out the awareness which can then start to tease some wisdom out of the situation.

198
00:27:36,430 --> 00:27:41,394
The next pairing is between the concentrated and unconcentrated mind.

199
00:27:43,857 --> 00:27:52,685
These refer to the two levels of concentration we encounter in Vipassana, termed vichara and vitaka in Pali.

200
00:27:56,230 --> 00:27:59,272
Vichara is described as applied thought.

201
00:28:01,275 --> 00:28:04,057
Here we're making an effort to focus the mind.

202
00:28:05,471 --> 00:28:07,193
We could be trying to follow the breath.

203
00:28:08,596 --> 00:28:13,761
Images and fantasies keep intruding, and we have to keep reminding ourselves of our goal.

204
00:28:13,821 --> 00:28:25,955
The notes, rising, falling, provide that reminder, like a lasso we throw around our scattered mind, drawing it back home.

205
00:28:28,638 --> 00:28:33,183
The image of a bee seeking nectar from a flower is also used.

206
00:28:34,952 --> 00:28:46,390
The flower is bobbing around in the breeze while the bee hovers a few inches away, tracking the flower to and fro, waiting for the exact moment to alight.

207
00:28:48,113 --> 00:28:55,083
When that opportunity comes, we have vitaka, described as sustained thought.

208
00:28:57,125 --> 00:29:00,791
This is a deeper, more restful level of concentration.

209
00:29:02,662 --> 00:29:08,920
Just as the bee is now being carried about by the flower, no longer needs to hover and track.

210
00:29:10,124 --> 00:29:17,885
We are being carried along by sensations and feelings, no longer needing any effort to maintain mindfulness.

211
00:29:21,140 --> 00:29:34,701
When we're following this particular exercise on the contemplation of mind, we're not so much trying to focus attention on the breath or other object as detecting whether or not we're focused.

212
00:29:36,403 --> 00:29:41,632
Are we putting some effort into containing images and thoughts, gathering them in?

213
00:29:41,692 --> 00:29:47,181
Or is the mind resting, being carried along by present experience?

214
00:29:49,269 --> 00:29:58,801
This is especially useful if we sense poor concentration as a problem in meditation and that we're failing because we don't have good concentration.

215
00:30:02,307 --> 00:30:12,779
It takes the pressure off as it no longer matters what the level of concentration is, only that we know whether we have to make an effort or whether we're relaxing.

216
00:30:17,063 --> 00:30:19,806
There are a number of other benefits to this exercise.

217
00:30:21,627 --> 00:30:29,057
One is that when we get interested in the unconcentrated mind we find we can now focus on this.

218
00:30:30,558 --> 00:30:34,502
So the lack of concentration actually leads to concentration.

219
00:30:37,507 --> 00:30:42,092
What I find is that the unconcentrated mind is divided.

220
00:30:42,712 --> 00:30:48,462
One desire chases a certain stream of thought, while another desire wants to chase another.

221
00:30:50,426 --> 00:30:55,474
The bee is hovering around a big bunch of flowers, can't decide which to alight upon.

222
00:30:58,621 --> 00:31:06,595
The general feeling of division is unpleasant, aversive, and thus we easily link this state with a sense of failure.

223
00:31:08,161 --> 00:31:18,076
Instead, we should simply recognise it as unconcentrated mind and see it as a worthy satipatthana exercise.

224
00:31:20,598 --> 00:31:23,864
A level of equanimity and tranquillity develops.

225
00:31:25,326 --> 00:31:30,574
This allows us make peace with the tendency towards restlessness, getting scattered.

226
00:31:35,380 --> 00:31:40,265
Focusing on the concentrated mind, we sense the pleasure of tranquillity.

227
00:31:42,326 --> 00:31:50,714
Of course, there is the danger of identification with this pleasant feeling, thinking, I am calm, and then grasping to the feeling.

228
00:31:52,476 --> 00:32:01,404
So here we are seeing the opposite to restlessness, the mind closing up within a pleasant haze, growing dull and lethargic.

229
00:32:02,920 --> 00:32:06,866
The bee has landed on the flower, but is sucking it dry.

230
00:32:09,471 --> 00:32:20,192
You do sometimes see a bee going to sleep on a flower, and in the same way we can actually lose consciousness when the mind is very concentrated.

231
00:32:21,775 --> 00:32:26,143
We're still sitting upright, but not registering anything consciously.

232
00:32:30,088 --> 00:32:43,394
Curiosity about the concentrated and unconcentrated mind prevents this closure and paradoxically I find I can actually start looking forward to losing concentration.

233
00:32:46,059 --> 00:32:52,553
I'm curious to discover what will be lost when concentration moves back to vichara.

234
00:32:56,380 --> 00:33:01,911
What I sometimes find is the mind moving from subjectivity to objectivity.

235
00:33:04,696 --> 00:33:13,275
If you remember back to the Sutta on the destruction of craving, the Buddha asks us to study the relationship between this and that.

236
00:33:14,622 --> 00:33:30,742
The concentrated mind, I find, is focusing on what it terms this, thinking of sensations and feelings as subjective, which is to be expected, as the feeling of a concentrated mind is pleasant.

237
00:33:31,884 --> 00:33:35,769
So we tend to think of this experience as me and mind.

238
00:33:37,336 --> 00:33:47,228
As concentration weakens, we notice unpleasant feelings which we label as that, as external, objective.

239
00:33:47,248 --> 00:33:50,792
Now we sense a division between the observer and the object.

240
00:33:54,237 --> 00:34:04,390
If there is enough equanimity, we can then focus more closely on the unpleasant sensations and concentration returns.

241
00:34:05,990 --> 00:34:19,289
We're again in the realm of subjectivity, but making peace with unpleasant feelings that we would normally externalise as some storyline about how badly the world treats us.

242
00:34:21,393 --> 00:34:34,612
The bee has alighted again, but on a thorny flower and needing constant encouragement not to fly off, to keep detecting the nectar that is on offer within the paint.

243
00:34:36,719 --> 00:34:58,170
Thus, the pairing of concentrated and unconcentrated mind can develop a very helpful relationship between these two where the unconcentrated mind is recognized as an opportunity to expand our mental horizons to make peace with a world that doesn't satisfy.

244
00:35:00,800 --> 00:35:13,375
Rob Barbilla, for many years the resident teacher at Gaia House, has a series of Dhamma talks titled In Praise of Restlessness, which I find very inspiring.

245
00:35:15,518 --> 00:35:23,246
He identifies the danger of overvaluing tranquillity so that we ignore anything that disturbs concentration.

246
00:35:26,264 --> 00:35:43,885
He uses Greek mythology to inspire us to value instead the mind that lacks tranquility, struggles with concentration, seeing this as a valiant, heroic attempt to embrace the tragic, crazy world with all its contradictions.

247
00:35:49,483 --> 00:35:56,233
The final pairing in this section of the Sutta is between the liberated and unliberated mind.

248
00:35:59,898 --> 00:36:03,764
Full liberation will only come at the moment of enlightenment.

249
00:36:05,086 --> 00:36:09,432
But the Buddha obviously wants us to practice this exercise before then.

250
00:36:11,876 --> 00:36:19,349
Anaglio suggests we interpret the liberated mind as one which is liberated from the view of self.

251
00:36:24,097 --> 00:36:32,231
Our usual effort in Vipassana is to be the objective observer, not interfering in any way, just observing.

252
00:36:34,014 --> 00:36:37,800
Bhante uses the analogy of a sailor on lookout duty.

253
00:36:39,467 --> 00:36:47,519
The sailor climbs up the mast to the crow's nest, a lookout post giving a broad overview of the ship and its surrounds.

254
00:36:49,041 --> 00:36:54,530
Without this lookout, the ship could strike rocks or run unprepared into a storm.

255
00:36:56,012 --> 00:37:04,344
In the same way, our position as objective observer lets us spot the telltale signs of desire, aversion, grasping.

256
00:37:05,742 --> 00:37:11,588
Instead of getting caught up in these, mindfulness lets us steer safely through the storm.

257
00:37:14,592 --> 00:37:16,815
Here we have the unsurpassed mind.

258
00:37:18,295 --> 00:37:20,498
The factors of enlightenment are strong.

259
00:37:23,041 --> 00:37:32,172
However, we are identifying as the observer and to that extent bound up in the dukkha which comes with identification.

260
00:37:36,606 --> 00:37:41,775
We usually aren't aware of this attachment till we lose the observer position.

261
00:37:43,938 --> 00:37:49,068
As far as we know, we're just watching equanimously, not interfering.

262
00:37:50,951 --> 00:38:01,347
But when thoughts begin to get sticky again, we realise we're slipping from our lofty perch on the crow's nest, falling into the bedlam we've been watching from above.

263
00:38:03,336 --> 00:38:11,210
Mindfulness of the dukkha which accompanies the fall from grace helps us lose attachment to the state of objective observer.

264
00:38:13,034 --> 00:38:26,458
It becomes easier to see the tough times when we get caught up and identified with thoughts and emotions as opportunities to develop compassion for our unenlightened condition.

265
00:38:30,809 --> 00:38:43,940
At times, when the factors are strong and we're in our crow's nest, observing objectively, the sense of ourselves as observer can simply disappear.

266
00:38:46,552 --> 00:38:54,268
There are sensations and feelings, perceptions and mental states, but these are just happening of their own accord.

267
00:38:54,309 --> 00:38:57,295
They no longer seem to be happening to me.

268
00:38:57,335 --> 00:39:01,001
There's no central reference point for it all.

269
00:39:05,199 --> 00:39:10,608
When we say that the sense of self disappears, this sounds like a form of death.

270
00:39:11,829 --> 00:39:15,755
But the disappearance is quiet, undramatic.

271
00:39:15,775 --> 00:39:19,101
It's not that there's a long struggle and we eventually surrender.

272
00:39:20,643 --> 00:39:24,610
It happens at times when we're not struggling, just watching.

273
00:39:29,458 --> 00:39:32,963
The sense of self is simply a mental construction.

274
00:39:34,967 --> 00:39:39,974
It's a perspective we're putting on experience, using our cognitive abilities.

275
00:39:42,699 --> 00:39:52,532
Cognition puts a shape on the millions of sensations, feelings, what we could call atoms of experience, registering each moment.

276
00:39:53,974 --> 00:39:57,880
It helps slow things down mentally, makes it all more manageable.

277
00:39:59,842 --> 00:40:04,248
One of the ways we frame experience is through the concept of self.

278
00:40:05,460 --> 00:40:14,114
We identify some of the atoms as me or mine and some as yours or his or some other way outside ourselves.

279
00:40:16,657 --> 00:40:18,300
But this distinction is learned.

280
00:40:20,204 --> 00:40:25,512
As a baby we weren't able to do this so it's not essential to life.

281
00:40:28,005 --> 00:40:36,315
It takes effort to frame experience like this, although the process is so habitual we don't notice that it's actually voluntary.

282
00:40:37,556 --> 00:40:42,041
We're willing ourselves to see the world as either self or other.

283
00:40:46,047 --> 00:40:56,358
At times in meditation the mind relaxes, stops making that effort, and the sense of self quietly disappears.

284
00:40:59,713 --> 00:41:05,202
This is the liberated mind, the experience of not-self, anatta.

285
00:41:08,485 --> 00:41:11,269
Sensations, feelings etc.

286
00:41:11,851 --> 00:41:17,920
continue to appear but we stop dividing these into boxes of mine or not mine.

287
00:41:20,903 --> 00:41:22,565
It's a joyful experience.

288
00:41:23,726 --> 00:41:32,088
We've dropped the burden of thinking of ourselves as someone with a future and a past and so many roles and responsibilities to uphold.

289
00:41:32,108 --> 00:41:36,036
In fact, there's seldom any desire to think.

290
00:41:36,858 --> 00:41:39,204
We're so riveted by present experience.

291
00:41:41,074 --> 00:41:47,623
Bhante uses the analogy of a baby who's so fascinated by what they're seeing that the jaw drops.

292
00:41:48,744 --> 00:41:53,751
They stare open-mouthed at the world in a state of total wonder.

293
00:41:59,056 --> 00:42:09,090
Although we probably won't want to think, the Buddha wants us to reflect that we are experiencing a mind that's been liberated from the view of self.

294
00:42:12,360 --> 00:42:18,628
This can actually be a challenge, as the absence of self may not be immediately apparent.

295
00:42:20,550 --> 00:42:22,731
We might not be able to work out what's happening.

296
00:42:23,532 --> 00:42:25,775
We just know we're seeing things differently.

297
00:42:26,976 --> 00:42:29,159
Experience is felt more intensely.

298
00:42:30,579 --> 00:42:33,402
There's no interest in anything but present experience.

299
00:42:34,483 --> 00:42:37,827
But other than that, everything continues normally.

300
00:42:40,001 --> 00:42:52,740
In her book, The Experience of No Self, Bernadette Roberts describes how she knew something had changed during a particular meditation, but couldn't work out what it was.

301
00:42:52,802 --> 00:43:06,161
She went about her daily business, she was a mother with teenage children, for a few days, till she suddenly realized that her sense of self had dropped away.

302
00:43:11,407 --> 00:43:17,556
Although the absence of self does not immediately trouble us, reflecting on this may trouble us.

303
00:43:19,438 --> 00:43:27,731
We fear what we do not understand and thus the very uptight self might emerge wanting to know what this implies.

304
00:43:28,731 --> 00:43:29,893
How can I be absent?

305
00:43:30,815 --> 00:43:32,858
How can the world be surviving without me?

306
00:43:32,898 --> 00:43:37,445
And so a multitude of contradictory thoughts may surface.

307
00:43:39,547 --> 00:43:41,110
Rather than follow these,

308
00:43:41,764 --> 00:43:52,074
we should simply reflect that this is the unliberated mind and feel the push and pull of desire and aversion underlying our fears and doubts.

309
00:43:55,038 --> 00:44:11,534
As we work mindfully through our fear of an atta, we start to appreciate the joy and freedom of the state, trusting that nothing essential is lost when we stop framing experience in terms of I, me, mind

310
00:44:13,135 --> 00:44:20,244
At times we may be able to study the transition from liberated to unliberated or vice versa.

311
00:44:21,746 --> 00:44:26,653
We see the effort of will that goes into framing experience in terms of self.

312
00:44:27,976 --> 00:44:30,579
Notice the relaxation as we stop.

313
00:44:36,148 --> 00:44:42,096
We might think that the liberated mind is always superior to the unliberated mind.

314
00:44:43,780 --> 00:44:51,009
But on this side of enlightenment anyhow, it is essential to be able to construct a sense of self at times.

315
00:44:52,871 --> 00:45:05,367
For example, we can learn to bring forth a sense of self that attaches firmly to notions of restraint in order to resist desires based in greed, hatred and delusion.

316
00:45:06,510 --> 00:45:16,061
When that work is done, our knowledge of the liberated mind helps us let go of attachment to the self who has just rescued us from this latest peril.

317
00:45:20,367 --> 00:45:27,996
In summary then, this section of the Satipatthana Sutta gives us five ways of probing the mind.

318
00:45:29,478 --> 00:45:54,422
asking whether it's contracted, meaning dull and lethargic, or distracted, restless, whether or not it's in an exalted state of goodwill, whether it's unsurpassed, can be developed further, or surpassed, has reached its limit for this session, whether it's concentrated,

319
00:45:55,532 --> 00:46:03,226
Has the bee landed on the flower, or is it hovering about, trying to track a flower that's bobbing about in the breeze?

320
00:46:06,092 --> 00:46:16,090
The final exercise is to ask whether the mind has been liberated from the sense of self, or whether we're identified as the observer.

321
00:46:19,731 --> 00:46:26,001
For each pairing we have the refrain, three variations on the basic exercise.

322
00:46:28,025 --> 00:46:35,036
First, we have the option to practice externally, to notice these mind states in others.

323
00:46:36,940 --> 00:46:44,693
When we've detected our mind is now exalted, we can reflect others' experience the exalted mind.

324
00:46:46,056 --> 00:46:53,224
And when we move to the unexalted state we can reflect others' experience and unexalted mind.

325
00:46:55,827 --> 00:46:58,389
We can do this for all of the five pairings.

326
00:46:59,771 --> 00:47:15,507
Realising that these states are part of the general human condition will loosen attachment, help us feel less ashamed of what we're deeming the less worthy states, less proud of those we judge as a terrific achievement.

327
00:47:17,257 --> 00:47:28,750
It also strengthens our goodwill and respect for others when we reflect that they can experience states like exalted mind, unsurpassed mind and liberated mind.

328
00:47:32,673 --> 00:47:37,480
The second option is to notice that these states arise and pass away.

329
00:47:37,519 --> 00:47:42,625
Again, this helps us let go of attachment.

330
00:47:44,139 --> 00:47:47,204
we might feel mightily proud of an unsurpassed mind.

331
00:47:48,405 --> 00:47:56,335
But if we reflect that this wasn't here a few minutes ago, we might also realise that this is just a temporary visitor.

332
00:47:57,436 --> 00:48:03,025
We should enjoy it while it's here, but not be too surprised when it fades away.

333
00:48:05,467 --> 00:48:09,472
The final option is simply to note there is mind.

334
00:48:12,625 --> 00:48:20,056
We're no longer trying to identify whether the mind is concentrated or surpassed or in any of the other states.

335
00:48:21,478 --> 00:48:29,530
This final option requires no effort whatsoever beyond focusing on the mind, the knowing aspect of experience.

336
00:48:31,934 --> 00:48:38,362
We could use the Mahasi note, knowing, knowing, to help maintain focus.

337
00:48:40,672 --> 00:48:49,961
The mind may pass through many of the states described, exalted, non-exalted, contracted, distracted, etc.

338
00:48:49,981 --> 00:48:54,867
We're letting all this happen quite naturally, organically.

339
00:48:56,429 --> 00:49:00,873
However, we're not making the effort to note exactly which state the mind is in.

340
00:49:02,175 --> 00:49:07,101
We're getting to know the mind intuitively, rather than by deliberate reflections.

341
00:49:08,853 --> 00:49:22,989
This is actually our normal Vipassana practice except that we're focusing on the mind, the knowing of experience, rather than our more usual focus on sensations and feelings.

342
00:49:25,391 --> 00:49:28,335
Let's finish with a verse from the Dhammapada.

343
00:49:29,657 --> 00:49:32,179
Mind is the forerunner of all evil.

344
00:49:33,762 --> 00:49:38,067
Speak or act with wicked mind, then suffering follows.

345
00:49:38,822 --> 00:49:41,989
even as the wheel follows the hoof of the ox.

346
00:49:44,916 --> 00:49:47,460
Mind is the forerunner of all good.

347
00:49:48,943 --> 00:49:57,320
Speak or act with pure mind, then happiness follows, even as the shadow that never leaves.

